commit_message:
liberty: release python-novaclient 2.30.2

This is a patch release request for a high priority bug fix where users
could request, by default, nova API microversions that the client does
not yet support which leads to failures.

Changes since 2.30.1:

mriedem@ubuntu:~/git/python-novaclient$ git log --oneline --no-merges
2.30.1..
dc49707 Set DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION to 2.5

Related-Bug: #1500688

Change-Id: Ide392b3a226d2f174e9b3627dbe183f5ff504f19

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-06-09 08:15:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I actually find the min max boot options useful. Especially the min option. You can say boot at least N instances or don't do anything.

I would rather look into making this API more useful"}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-06-10 07:50:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Realistically wouldn't most people that want to boot more than one instance be using an orchestration engine of some kind so that they can continue managing them as a group after they're up and running?"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-06-10 10:12:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Also the EC2 API needs this feature.'}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-06-11 05:58:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Couldn't the EC2 API call the nova API multiple times to boot multiple instances?  (And I believe the in-tree EC2 API is deprecated and so presumably will be removed eventually.)"}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-06-11 12:39:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

IHMO no the EC2 API cannot easily call nova multiple times. That works for "max" but not for "min"'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2015-06-12 10:18:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-08-11 19:45:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Honestly, I'm in favor of cutting off this interface. I'm not sure I understand why EC2 api can't call Nova multiple times."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2015-09-28 19:48:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

With a task record, we'd have a very clear view of the progress of a multiboot.

I encounter people using multiboot quite a bit in real world situations. I don't really see any reason to remove it, requiring those people to just hit the API harder to achieve the same result.

Do we have feedback from operators that this is not used and that removing it would be uncontroversial? If not, I see no reason to remove it."}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-09-28 19:53:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

If we don't remove it, then we should probably fix up https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1458122

If I ask to boot "a min of 3 and a max of 5" instances, and the system can schedule 4, then that request should count as successful.'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2015-09-29 13:18:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

We probably want to fix that yes but not remove that option. I cannot believe we do not have a real and big earn between a single multiboot call vs several hits.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-10-01 14:15:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

The API itself is probably useful - the way it's implemented internally is bad. I'd probably also lean towards keeping it (although I think it's used mostly for stress testing and it's actual usefulness is limited).

I am much more interested in starting a conversation on removing features. Removing missfeatures should not be tied to API versioning. It should happen much quicker!"}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:48:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

Removing a feature completely (rather than waiting for it to "age out" via microversions) would violate the API guarantees that we provide.  Once it's released, I think we're locked into keeping it around for a while.'}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:55:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

What I am saying is that we should change the API guarantees. At this point the timeline is basically forever. This practically means features can't be removed. This is generally a very bad thing for a project."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2015-10-01 15:57:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-10-01 17:26:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

"Deprecations for features should not be tied to the API i.e. should be a special case that is treated differently."

If you remove a feature that is exposed in the API, then you are affecting the API.

With semver that would require a major number bump due to not-backwards-compatible changes.  In nova it would be the equivalent of increasing the minimum microversion.

We can still do it, it just means that we break backwards-compatibility with old clients.  (Which is exactly what we are doing by removing the feature.)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-11-05 12:24:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-2

So I don't think we can drop this API. We agreed not to discuss raising the min_version until Barcelona. Honestly, I can't see us ever raising the min_version.

Now I think we should have a quota for the max _count that is supported? Maybe a policy to disable it? Would that help with your concerns?"}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-11-05 15:27:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm fine with leaving in support for booting multiple instances.  However, in that case we need to fix https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1458122 because it just makes no sense to error out when we can actually boot up the requested min_count instances.

I might be able to propose a patch in the not-too-distant future."}, {'account_id': 8768, 'date': '2015-11-05 15:27:34.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoned due to lack of interest.'}]

commit_message:
Drop support for booting multiple instances

Currently nova allows the caller to specify "min_count" and "max_count"
parameters in order to cause multiple instances to be booted in one call.
Currently there is no good way for an end user to get information about how
many instances were successfully booted, and if so which ones were booted as a
result of that call. Since we now have orchestration outside of nova which does
a better job of keeping track of that sort of thing, let's drop support for
booting multiple instances from nova.

APIImpact
Implements blueprint no-multiple-instance-boot

Change-Id: I7bdd2324a958d550f964479790b2a22c1941c0cc

commit_message:
XtremIO fix create CG from src flow

Fix a bug suring creating volume with CG,
    that prevented the volume from being added to the CG on the array.
Query array snapshots names for CG snapshot before copying them
    to a new volume.
Add unittest for create_cg_from_src.

liberty-backport-potential

Change-Id: Ida6eb3f7198f7050d8c27fe5560ac8980bb4f0df
Closes-Bug: #1512682

commit_message:
Rename fernet methods to match expiration timestamp

Fernet tokens carry the token creation time as part of the Fernet
specification, which is an integer. This is not the case with the token
expiration time, which is carried in the payload of the Fernet token. Keystone
converts the timestamp to a floating point value to save space in the token.
Previously, all the methods handling this conversion, along with the related
tests, communicated that this conversion was to an integer instead of a
float. This change corrects the methods signatures in the Fernet token provider
to be consistent with the timestamp type that is used in the implementation.

Conflicts:
	keystone/token/providers/fernet/token_formatters.py

Change-Id: Ibea9fa0d546948501ebcd9f9f826b1f1319246f2
(cherry picked from commit 94904b305b74e4e9e1b70b7c6e1351febdd6862d)

commit_message:
Log end of router updates for PD and delete branches

These execution branches call continue directly without
logging the end of the router update.  This leads to
confusion about when the last router update finishes if
it is a delete or a PD update.

Change-Id: Id82e7374aa9336e0adea3042238f30f716208373
Signed-off-by: Ryan Moats <rmoats@us.ibm.com>
Closes-bug: #1511004
(cherry picked from commit 70b3d383ac2a0d7d339c551065b9b378a4b9b914)
